 @{b}@{u}@{fg shine}HotKey Bank   @{ub}@{uu}@{fg text}

   Hotkey banks give you possibility to be more restrictive in
 hotkey  selection  process. Usage is very simple: if key doesn't exists
 in loaded bank it is not allowed to use it. Of course this feature is
 optional, so you should set it to @{b}OFF@{ub} whenever you don't need
 it.

   Creating hotkey banks is very simple and can be made with any text
 editor (ED, CED, GoldED etc). You may make this file as long as you
 need, however internally HotKey keeps only 256 characters (as there's no
 more ASCII codes used). It does not means it will truncate your file
 after reading first 256 bytes! Load routine is smart enough to avoid
 duplicates, so don't worry. Take a look at enclosed banks for example.


 @{b}@{u}@{fg shine}Dictionary  @{ub}@{uu}@{fg text}

 *** I'll describe it later (It's not functional yet anyway :-) ***


 @{b}@{u}@{fg shine}Locked keys   @{ub}@{uu}@{fg text}

   Using locked keys you may define these keys which you don't want to
 be allowed (e.g. you should type "SUC" if you got "SAVE", "USE",
 "CANCEL" gadgets visible all the time and you don't want to have
 duplicated keys for other buttons).


 @{b}@{u}@{fg shine}Status column  @{ub}@{uu}@{fg text}

   Status column describes status of each line. It mostly indicated
 errors, so it's advised to make all entries correct before you run the
 resolver. Possible states are indicated by single letter. For better
 editing all strings being in abnormal state will be highlighted. And
 here's the meaning of the letters:

   @{b}@{fg shine}B@{ub}@{fg text} - hotkey you wish to use for the string doesn't exist in loaded
       HotKey bank and therefore (if bank is choosen correctly) may
       not be usable within the app.

       @{fg shine}Solutions:@{fg text}

        1. Choose other key
        2. Leave this field blank and let program find the proper one
        3. Load correct HotKey bank or expand the one you use (be
           careful adding new keys).
        4. Check correctness of state of CaseSensitive mode switch
           and adjust if necessary

   @{b}@{fg shine}D@{ub}@{fg text} - hotkey you wish to use for this string is already used for other one
       (check above strings).

       @{fg shine}Solutions:@{fg text}

        1. Choose other key
        2. Leave this field blank and let program find the proper one
        3. Check correctness of state of CaseSensitive mode switch
           and adjust if necessary

   @{b}@{fg shine}L@{ub}@{fg text} - hotkey you wish to use for this string is defined as locked one
       and therefore further using may cause problems within the app
       (mainly duplicated hotkeys).

       @{fg shine}Solutions:@{fg text}

        1. Choose other key
        2. Leave this field blank and let program find the proper one
        3. Adjust locked keys
       
   @{b}@{fg shine}R@{ub}@{fg text} - Resolver coudn't choose correct hotkey for the string. Possible
       reasons are:

        1. All letters were used for other strings (resolver acts
           on each entry of the list, starting at the topmost).
        2. Resolver works in StrictMode and no letter existing in the
           string left unused.
        3. Resolver works in StrictMode with CaseSensitive option and
           no letter existing in the string, matching proper capitation,
           left unused.

       @{fg shine}Solutions:@{fg text}

        1. Choose key manually
        2. Drag string at the top of the list.
        3. Check state of StrictMode switch and adjust if necessary
        4. Check state of CaseSensitive switch and adjust if necessary
        5. Change (extend) the string if possible



 @{b}@{u}@{fg shine}Sugestion column   @{ub}@{uu}@{fg text}

   In this column you will find program sugestions displayed
 everytime you run the resolver. You may accept the all using
 @{b}Accept sugestions@{ub} menu item (they will appear in
 Key column) or clear them all using @{b}Clear all sugested
 hotkeys@{ub}.


 @{b}@{u}@{fg shine}Key column   @{ub}@{uu}@{fg text}

   In this column you will find hotkeys which are defined to be
 used for given string.


 @{b}@{u}@{fg shine}String column   @{ub}@{uu}@{fg text}

   As you can see, here is the base string displayed.


 @{b}@{u}@{fg shine}String, HotKey and NoKey gadgets  @{ub}@{uu}@{fg text}

   You can type your string in this gadget whenever you define new
 one, or edit existing one if you are just doing so. If you have already
 chosen the key for the string, just type it using @{b}HotKey@{ub} gadget.
 If you wish the string to have no key (it makes such entry almost
 senseless in this application (except for cases you temporairly
 disabled it for testing etc), but it you want to have all your strings
 here, you just have such possibility), use @{b}No Key@{ub} gadget.
 @{b}NOTE:@{ub} your hotkey will @{b}not@{ub} be lost if you use @{b}No Key@{ub} checkmark.
 It will be shown on the display any longer, but will be kept in memory
 and saved with the whole project as well. If you change your mind, you
 can always restore it by switching @{b}No Key@{ub} off. If there was
 any key defined before, it simply appears again.
 

 @{b}@{u}@{fg shine}New and Delete gadgets  @{ub}@{uu}@{fg text}

   Using this gadgets you can create new entries in the database
 or kill existing ones.

@endnode

